		{
			"name": "3. WebSocket",
			"description": "WebSocket endpoints for real-time notifications.\n\n**Test WS (no auth):**\n```\nws://{{base_url}}/test/ws/notifications?user_id=1\n```\n\n**Production WS (JWT):**\n```\nws://{{base_url}}/status/notifications/ws/notifications?token={{token}}\n```\n\n**UI Proxy WS (no auth, port 5009):**\n```\nws://localhost:5009/ws/notifications?user_id=1\n```\n\n**Messages from server:**\n```json\n{\"type\": \"unread_count\", \"data\": {\"count\": 5}}\n{\"type\": \"notification\", \"data\": {\"id\": 1, \"title\": \"...\", ...}}\n{\"type\": \"banner\", \"action\": \"create\", \"data\": {...}}\n{\"type\": \"pong\"}\n```\n\n**Messages to server:**\n```json\n{\"action\": \"ping\"}\n{\"action\": \"mark_read\", \"notification_id\": 123}\n```\n\nNote: Postman supports WebSocket testing via the WebSocket Request tab (New → WebSocket Request).",
			"item": []
		}
	]
}
